"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385099","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p>This data is not held centrally and collating it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-30T14:59:59.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385099/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385099/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have been released having served no more than (a) half and (b) a quarter of their sentence for offences of each type in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385100","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>Access to in-cell television is a key earnable privilege under the Incentives and Earned Privileges policy framework. Access is not permitted for prisoners who do not engage with their rehabilitation or co-operate with the prison regime. Prisoners must pay a weekly rental charge to cover the costs of providing televisions.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested is at Annex E of Prison Service Instruction 30/2013, Incentives and Earned Privileges, which can be accessed at: <a title="http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2013" href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2013" target="_blank">http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2013</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T15:46:19.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385100/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385100/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisons: Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which television channels are available to prisoners.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385101","Ministry of Justice","true","2015-07-01","<p>Prisoners are not allowed electronic tablet devices<ins class="ministerial"> </ins><ins class="ministerial">or laptops that are able to access the internet in their cells</ins>. The other information requested is not held centrally and can be obtained only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on access to games consoles is available on page 20 of Prison Service Instruction 30/2013, Incentives and Earned Privileges, which can be accessed at: <a title="http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2013" href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2013" target="_blank">http://www.justice.gov.uk/offenders/psis/prison-service-instructions-2013</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T16:59:25.067Z","2015-09-03T15:52:05.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385101/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385101/answer","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385101/answer/previousversion/10608","Biography information for Andrew Selous","54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisons: Electronic Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have (a) games consoles, (b) tablets and (c) telephones in their cells.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385102","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>Prisoners in England are entitled to receive NHS healthcare treatments equivalent to those received by people in the community.</p><p> </p><p>NHS treatment for post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) is provided according to clinical need and informed by best practice guidelines. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) provides detailed guidance (NICE Clinical Guideline 26) on treating PTSD, which NHS health professionals are expected to take into account when deciding best practice, or which treatment to provide. NICE Clinical Guideline 26 applies to prisoners and people in the community, including former service personnel.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A copy of NICE Clinical Guideline 26 has been placed in the Library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All prisoners with a military history are eligible for the full range of interventions and services available in NOMS ‘Core Rehabilitative Offer’. In prison, Governors have responsibility for reviewing the needs of their population and planning appropriate services to meet those needs. In addition, armed services charities - including The Royal British Legion (TRBL), SSAFA, and Combat Stress - send caseworkers to support and work with ex-ASP in some prisons. These services will also be available to CRCs and the National Probation Service (NPS). The JustMentoring website, set up originally by NOMS and now managed by the charity Clinks, also actively promotes the work of these charities.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T16:50:18.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385102/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385102/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what support is available to former service personnel diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder who have been sentenced to prison.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385103","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The available information is given in the table and is taken from the Home Office Homicide Index.</p><p>Data are based on the number of homicides where the male victim’s relationship to the principal suspect was defined as partner or ex-partner.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-29T10:17:20.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385103/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385103/answer","Table for PQ 3768.xls","Offences recorded as homicide","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385103/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-23","Domestic Abuse: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many men were killed by their current or former partner in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385104","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>The department does not hold the information requested .</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-07-01T16:39:15.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385104/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385104/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information his Department holds on the number of states party to the European Convention on Human Rights, the prisons of which breach any term of that convention.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385105","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-02","<p>The UK has concluded compulsory transfer agreements with Nigeria and with Albania. The first prisoners have been transferred under these arrangements and we expect to see a slow build up in the numbers transferred as the processes are embedded in both countries. Compulsory transfer processes are complex, involving the courts in both countries, and requiring the consent of the recipient country on a case-by-case basis. A MoU providing for compulsory transfer to Somaliland is also in place. We are currently negotiating a compulsory PTA with Ghana and exploring opportunities for compulsory PTAs with other countries where prison standards meet the minimum international requirements. Neither I nor the Secretary of State plan to make a statement on this matter.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-07-02T08:47:10.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385105/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385105/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress has been made on compulsory prisoner transfers to non-EU countries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385106","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>The average length of custodial sentences handed down by magistrates’ courts in England and Wales, from 2012 to 2014, can be viewed on the Ministry of Justice website and it is available at the following link:-</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong><a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014</a></strong></p><p> </p><p>Select and open “Magistrates’ court data tool”</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Data held centrally for reporting purposes on the time served in custody does not reliably record whether it was a magistrates’ or Crown Court that imposed the sentence. To answer this question, we would therefore need to match together prison releases and court sentencing data, which could only be undertaken at a disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T12:23:18.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385106/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385106/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length was of (a) custodial sentences handed down by magistrates' courts and (b) time subsequently served in prison by people who received those sentences in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385107","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p /> <p>As at 31 March 2015, 1.1% of the total prison population that have ethnicity declarations recorded on central systems identified themselves as having Irish Traveller or Gypsy background. Over 98% of all prisoners have such declarations recorded.</p><p> </p><p>A survey by HM Inspectorate of Prisons, published in 2014, suggested that some 5% of prisoners identified themselves with a broader category of Gypsy, Romany or Traveller.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T14:27:44.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385107/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385107/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of prisoners identify as being from a Gypsy, Traveller or Roma background.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385108","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p>Prisons decide locally whether to engage in activities such as Gypsy, Roma, Traveller History Month or whether they organise Traveller days. This information is not held centrally, and could be collected only at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-30T16:17:24.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385108/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385108/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisons: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which prisons (a) are holding events to mark Gypsy, Roma, Traveller History Month and (b) have organised Traveller days in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385109","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>There are currently no plans to meet Ministers in the Scottish Government to discuss employment tribunal fees.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-07-01T12:05:14.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385109/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385109/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Employment Tribunals Service: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to meet with Ministers in the Scottish Government as part of his Department's review of employment tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","3798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385110","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-02","<p /> <p>There are a number of different ways costs of cases can be estimated, depending on how indirect costs are apportioned, resulting in range of cost estimates for these cases. The latest period for which data is available is 2012-13 (up-rated to 2014-15 prices). The costs include judiciary, staff, estates and overhead costs.</p><p>a) A guilty plea entered on the day of a trial at the Crown court would result in a cracked trial. The cost of a cracked trial in the Crown court is estimated to be between £1,200 and £2,000 (to the nearest £100).</p><p>b) The cost of an either way guilty plea entered at the Magistrates Court is estimated to be between £210 and £270 (to the nearest £10).</p><p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service does not record this data on a routine basis. The 2012-13 data was extracted as part of the implementation work on the Criminal Court Charge. A review of the Criminal Court Charge will be completed later in 2015-16 and we anticipate more up to date data will be collected and made available, if requested, at that point.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-02T12:20:10.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385110/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385110/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Criminal Proceedings: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average cost is of an either way offence case dealt with at the (a) Crown Court and (b) magistrates' court where a guilty plea was entered.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385111","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p /> <p>As at 31 March 2015 in England and Wales, there were 1,049 indeterminate sentenced prisoners in open prisons, of which 511 were serving life sentences and 538 were serving an indeterminate sentence of imprisonment for public protection.</p><p> </p><p>The figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p><p> </p><p>The categorisation and allocation of any offender to open prison is never an automatic progression, with public protection the paramount consideration in the decision-making process. Only prisoners whose risks are assessed as being manageable in conditions of low security will be allocated to an open prison.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of indeterminate sentence prisoners will be transferred to open conditions only following a positive recommendation from the independent Parole Board. Where they can show that they have made exceptional progress and where there are no known or documented concerns about their risk of harm or risk of abscond, they may be transferred without a positive recommendation from the Parole Board.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, decisive action was taken to protect the public by changing the policy by which prisoners may be transferred to open conditions. As a result of a comprehensive review, major changes were made to tighten the eligibility for open prisons. Prisoners may no longer be transferred to open conditions or allowed to be released on temporary licence if they have, on the current sentence, previously absconded, escaped, attempted to escape, or if they have failed to return or have re-offended whilst released on temporary licence, unless there are exceptional circumstances.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T14:38:20.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385111/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385111/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Open Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners who are in open prisons are serving (a) a life and (b) an indeterminate sentence for public protection.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385112","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Information requested is not currently available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-06-30T15:06:49.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385112/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385112/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Trials: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average cost is of (a) a jury trial at the Crown Court for (i) either way offences sent by magistrates where their sentencing powers were not deemed sufficient, (ii) either way offences where the defendant chose to elect jury trial and (iii) indictable only offences and (b) a trial in a magistrates' court for (A) summary only offences and (B) either way offences in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385113","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>Prisons use a comprehensive range of security measures to detect, disrupt and deter the trafficking of illegal items into prisons. Despite these measures there will always be attempts made to smuggle items to prisoners. It is a requirement for prisons to record centrally instances where drugs, mobile phones, firearms and ammunition are discovered in prison.</p><p> </p><p>During the period 1 February to 31 May 2015 there were instances recorded where drugs and mobile phones were discovered in packages<sup>1</sup> sent into prisoners.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup> “Packages” includes those incoming items recorded as “parcels”, “post”, “mail” or “packages”</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T14:17:00.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385113/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385113/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisons: Parcels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether any illegal items have been found in packages sent to prisoners since 1 February 2015.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385114","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Criminal Procedure Rules place the responsibility for alerting the court to any defendant’s previous convictions, both domestic and overseas, whether for the purposes of bail or for the purposes of sentencing, on the prosecutor.</p><p> </p><p>Courts must give consideration to that information when it is available but rely on the Police to obtain and provide it.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-30T14:20:31.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385114/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385114/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Criminal Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to ensure that courts are aware of the foreign criminal convictions of (a) foreign and (b) British criminals for the purposes of bail and sentencing.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385115","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p>Data on the number of books sent to prisoners since 1 February 2015 is not held centrally, and could only be collected at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-30T14:50:07.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385115/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385115/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisons: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many books have been sent to prisoners since 1 February 2015.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385116","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>Information on custodial sentences given in the magistrates’ court is available at</p><p> </p><p><a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428944/magistrates-court-data-tool.xls" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428944/magistrates-court-data-tool.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/428944/magistrates-court-data-tool.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>The maximum sentence that can be given for a single offence at the magistrates’ court is six months for an adult therefore any sentence longer than that results from sentencing for multiple offences.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T12:32:40.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385116/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385116/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Magistrates Courts: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and in what proportion of cases offenders in magistrates' courts received a (a) six-month immediate custodial sentence for one offence and (b) 12-month custodial sentence for two or more offences in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385117","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-01","<p>In 2014, the average number of days that male prisoners were released on temporary licence (ROTL) was 59 days and the average number of days that female prisoners were released on temporary licence was 48 days. Over the course of the year, a total of 8,072 men and 731 women had at least one day of temporary release.</p><p> </p><p>In the past 18 months we have made major changes to the policy and practice around temporary release applying equally to men and women, improving the risk assessment, monitoring and review of ROTL so that this important rehabilitative tool can continue to be used where appropriate and without putting the public at risk. In 2014, instances of ROTL have reduced by 14%, and the number of ROTL failures has fallen by 39%. At 53 failures per 100,000 releases, it was the lowest ROTL failure rate since 2002.</p><p> </p><p>These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-07-01T16:21:43.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385117/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385117/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average number of days was that (a) male and (b) female prisoners were released on temporary licence during the latest year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","3812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385118","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-29","<p>The number of deaths in custody has increased in recent years, as the prison population and the proportion of older prisoners within it have increased.</p><p> </p><p>The table attached shows the number of prisoners who have died in each prison in each of the last six months for which annual data has been published. The annual information on deaths in each prison is published in the Safety in Custody statistics available at <a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2014-and-annual" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2014-and-annual" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2014-and-annual</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-29T16:59:14.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385118/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385118/answer","3875 - Deaths in Custody.xls","Deaths in Custody","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385118/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have died in each prison in each of the last six months.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","3875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385119","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-29","<p>Every death in custody is subject to investigation by the police. The decisions as to whether or not to treat a particular death as a suspected homicide, and what information to disclose about the status of each ongoing investigation, are matters for the relevant police authorities in each case.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-29T13:31:38.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385119/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385119/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisoners: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many deaths in custody are under investigation by police as suspected homicide.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","3874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385120","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-29","<p>This information is published in the Safety in Custody statistics available at <a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2014-and-annual" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2014-and-annual" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-december-2014-and-annual</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2015-06-29T13:06:48.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385120/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385120/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-23","Prisons: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many homicides in prison have taken place in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","3873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385121","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-29","<p>I intend to publish proposals for English votes for English laws shortly. Following this announcement I will ensure that there is time for full and thorough debate in the House.</p><p><br>I am encouraged to learn of the hon. lady's impatience for the delivery of English votes for English laws and hope that she will play a full part in the scrutiny of these proposals.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2015-06-29T16:48:35.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385121/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385121/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-23","English Votes for English Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether he plans to publish his proposals for English votes for English laws before 21 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","3872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385122","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>Youth unemployment in Northern Ireland has fallen by 1.1 percentage points over the year, from 20.0 per cent in February-April 2014, to 18.9 per cent in February-April 2015.</p><p>The Government has abolished employer National Insurance Contributions for under-21 year olds from April 2015 making it cheaper for businesses in Northern Ireland to employ young people.</p><p>As part of our long term economic plan, the Government is also reducing the largest structural deficit in UK peacetime history. This is essential to deliver a sustainable economic recovery to assist young people to get job opportunities in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-30T11:27:53.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385122/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385122/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-23","Unemployment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent progress the Government has made on reducing youth unemployment levels in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385123","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>In the course of my duties I have regular meetings and maintain regular contact with Ministers from the Irish Government.</p><p>These meetings and discussions cover a wide range of issues which are relevant to the situation in Northern Ireland at that time; this would sometimes include general conversations on parading. I do not discuss individual Parades Commission determinations with the Irish Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-29T15:21:32.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385123/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385123/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-23","Parades: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with her Irish counterpart on parades in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385124","Prime Minister","false","2015-06-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the speech I gave on 18 June 2015, a transcript of which can be found on the gov.uk, in which I say that <em>“if you’re a troubled boy who is angry at the world, or a girl looking for an identity, for something to believe in and there’s something that is quietly condoned online, or perhaps even in parts of your local community, then it’s less of a leap to go from a British teenager to an ISIL fighter or an ISIL wife, than it would be for someone who hasn’t been exposed to these things</em>”.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-06-30T16:39:55.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385124/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385124/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-06-23","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what the evidential basis was for his statement that British Muslims quietly condoned extremism made at the Global Security Forum in Bratislava on 18 June 2015.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","3929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385125","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-02","<p>I have not discussed Firefighters’ Pension Scheme Reforms with the Scottish Government. The design of the reformed Firefighter Pension Scheme was led by Roseanna Cunningham MSP when Minister for Community Safety and the administration of both the new and old Fire Pension Schemes in Scotland falls to the Scottish Public Pensions Agency which is an agency of the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-02T14:17:19.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385125/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385125/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-23","Fire Services: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on Firefighters' Pension Scheme reforms.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","3619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385126","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-02","<p>I have not made representations to the Department for Communities and Local Government on the effect of Firefighters’ Pension Scheme reforms in Scotland. The design of the reformed Firefighter Pension Scheme was led by Roseanna Cunningham MSP when Minister for Community Safety and the implementing regulations were laid before the Scottish Parliament on 11 March 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-02T14:19:21.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385126/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385126/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-23","Fire Services: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what representations he has made to the Department for Communities and Local Government on the effect of Firefighters' Pension Scheme reforms in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","3620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385127","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-02","<p>I meet regularly with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions and we discuss a wide range of issues including welfare provision. The reasons behind foodbank use are complex and can be affected by issues that are already the responsibility of the Scottish Government in areas such as education, health and social care, housing and justice.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-02T15:20:38.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385127/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385127/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-23","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will discuss levels of food bank use in Scotland with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions in order to assess the potential link between reductions in welfare provision and food bank usage.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","3621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385128","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-02","<p>I meet regularly with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions to discuss a wide range of welfare related matters. The Government believes that unemployment benefits must be conditional on recipients taking action to find work if we are to maintain confidence in the welfare system. This is a view shared by most practitioners and the Scottish Government’s own Expert Group.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-02T14:21:04.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385128/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385128/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-23","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what representations he has made to the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on changing the benefit sanctions regime in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","3622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385129","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The maximum speed of the bi-mode and electric IEP trains in regular service will be the maximum permitted line speed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The information relating to electric and bi-mode IEP trains in 5 and 9 car formations can be found in the Train Technical Specification available on the Department of Transport website.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T16:27:16.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385129/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385129/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how long it will take for (a) electric IEP trains and (b) other bi-mode IEP trains running on diesel to reach 125 mph on flat and straight track in (i) five and (ii) nine car formations.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385130","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Rail Delivery Group (RDG) has not published an annual report. However, summaries of all RDG meetings since June 2011 are available on the RDG website at:</p><p><a href="http://www.raildeliverygroup.com/what-we-do/publications/rdg-meetings.html" target="_blank">http://www.raildeliverygroup.com/what-we-do/publications/rdg-meetings.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The RDG has also published the agenda and summary of proceedings of its Industry Day at:</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p><a href="http://www.raildeliverygroup.com/what-we-do/events/rdg-events/rdg-industry-days/previous-rdg-industry-days.html" target="_blank">http://www.raildeliverygroup.com/what-we-do/events/rdg-events/rdg-industry-days/previous-rdg-industry-days.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T13:21:17.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385130/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385130/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Rail Delivery Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will place in the Library copies of all Rail Delivery Group Annual Reports held by his Department.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385131","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>There are no such outsourced services. Decisions regarding outsourcing are commercial ones best made by the operator, not dictated by the Department.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T14:51:26.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385131/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385131/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what services are outsourced under the Greater Anglia rail franchise; and whether he plans to require such services to be brought in-house when the next such franchise is let.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385132","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Department has already engaged in preliminary discussions with Nexus to explore options for the replacement of rolling stock on the Tyne &amp; Wear Metro.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government has also provided £350m towards the cost of upgrading and renewing the current network. Part of this funding has allowed Nexus to refurbish the current fleet.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T11:49:10.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385132/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385132/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Tyne and Wear Metro","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to support the replacement of rolling stock on the Tyne and Wear Metro.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","3854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385133","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Department for Transport allocates capital funding grants for local highways maintenance and integrated transport block to local highway authorities. This funding is not ring-fenced and it is entirely for each highway authority to decide, based on their needs and priorities, as to how this funding is spent.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T10:54:40.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385133/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385133/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what flexibility exists between his Department's maintenance and integrated transport budgets to enable funding to be re-allocated to increase spending on road maintenance.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","3797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385134","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Final journey time improvements will not be confirmed until the passenger service timetable is published.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T14:55:08.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385134/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385134/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Rolling Stock: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 22 June 2015 to Question 3011, whether the (a) London and Bristol, (b) London and Cardiff, (c) London and Swansea, (d) London and York, (e) London and Newcastle, (f) London and Edinburgh, (g) Edinburgh and Inverness and (h) Edinburgh and Aberdeen routes are expected to experience the expected 15 minute journey time improvements.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385135","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-30","<p>In the UK airports, and the airlines that use them, operate in a competitive, commercial environment. It is for individual airlines make market-based decisions regarding the air services that they operate, and from which airports. It is not open to the Government to compel airlines to operate air services between specific airports.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-30T13:40:58.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385135/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385135/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Heathrow Airport: Belfast City Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to maintain the current level of connectivity between Heathrow Airport and Belfast City Airport before a decision is reached on additional runway capacity in South East England.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385136","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-30","<p>On 25 June the Secretary of State announced that Great Western was a top priority for delivery.　We are committed to electrifying the Great Western line to Swansea and are contributing £125million to the Welsh Government’s Valley Lines electrification scheme. A huge amount of investment will be going into Wales, in terms not only of the track, but the new trains.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The Secretary of State also described some of the challenges Network Rail is facing. That is why he has asked the new chair of Network Rail to develop proposals by the Autumn for how the rail upgrade programme will be carried out.</p><p /> <p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p><strong></strong></p><p /><p><strong></strong></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-30T13:54:28.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385136/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385136/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Great Western Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, by what date he expects electrification of the Great Western Line to Swansea and Valleys Lines in Wales to be completed.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385137","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-30","<p>The commissioned Hitachi trains for the Great Western line will have two configurations, one running on electric power and a second bi-mode capable of running on either diesel or electric power.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-30T13:58:17.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385137/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385137/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Great Western Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the commissioned Hitachi trains intended for the Great Western Line are able to run on both diesel and electricity.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385138","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>As the Prime Minister recently stated, we are absolutely committed to electrifying the Great Western mainline to Cardiff and through to Swansea and are contributing £125million to the costs of the wider Valley Lines electrification scheme.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T13:44:03.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385138/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385138/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Great Western Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to reduce the extent of the electrification on the Great Western Line.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385140","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>In order to reduce costs, we no longer publish a printed version of the Department for Transport organisational chart. We publish an online version at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>.　Following the General Election this is currently being updated and will be available by the end of July.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>We are planning to publish Q3 and Q4 2014/2015 transparency data by mid-July and currently working on the timetable for 2015/2016.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>As a regulator independent of government, the Office of Rail and Road’s (ORR) arrangements for publication of its Board minutes are a matter for the ORR Board.　 Network Rail is an arm’s-length public sector body and its arrangements for the publication of the minutes of its Board meetings remain operational matters for the company.　 However, I understand that both bodies advise that they aim to publish their Board minutes within three months.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-29T11:36:36.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385140/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385140/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Department for Transport: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish his Department's updated organisation chart; if he will update his Department's Ministerial transparency data series for the period since March 2014; and if he will encourage Network Rail and the Office of Rail and Road to publish their Board minutes no later than three months after those meetings occur.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385141","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Our plans for simplifying regulated fares within the fares baskets for the Northern Invitation To Tender do not depend solely on bidders' use of the flex mechanism. Whilst the flex mechanism provides one means for train operators to rebalance fares over time to remove the sharp jumps and anomalies that currently occur, fares simplification can nonetheless take place within the Northern franchise without the use of the flex. We expect to work with the future Northern franchisee to explore which approaches would be most appropriate to phase out these anomalies over the long-term.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T11:28:15.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385141/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385141/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 22 June 2015 to Question 2634, and with reference to the Northern franchise invitation to tender of 27 February 2015, whether his plans to enable the simplification of regulated fares structures within the consolidated fares baskets that invitation to tender were dependent on bidders' use of the flex mechanism; and what alternative mechanisms are available to bidders for that franchise for the purpose of simplifying overall regulated fare structures.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","3925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385142","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Government has no plans to devolve responsibilities in relation to Network Rail’s delivery of the current five-year Rail Investment Strategy (RIS). We are working closely with the Welsh Government on the development of options for the next RIS for the period 2019-2024.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans to restructure Network Rail.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-30T14:05:29.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385142/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385142/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-23","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to devolve Network Rail functions to the Welsh Government; and whether he plans to restructure Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385143","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-01","<p>Our policy is to award contracts on the basis of the best value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the composition of suppliers’ boards and their pay structures is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘Think, Act, Report’ initiative is a simple framework to help businesses maximise female talent in the workplace. Over 280 businesses, covering over 2.5 million employees, have signed up to the principles embodied in ‘Think, Act, Report’. They are listed on the Gov.uk website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/companies-signed-up-to-think-act-report/companies-signed-up-to-think-act-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/companies-signed-up-to-think-act-report/companies-signed-up-to-think-act-report</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","3694 ; 3695 ; 3696 ; 3697 ; 3698 ; 3699 ; 3715","2015-07-01T16:07:42.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385143/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/385143/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-23","Government Contracts: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of companies with a Government contract worth more than £10,000 have a Board of Directors of which at least 50 per cent of its members are women.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","3714"
