, what assets are currently owned by the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and its non-departmental public bodies; and what prospective asset sales are under review by the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs.","false","Biography information for Baroness Parminter",,"Baroness Parminter","HL719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384509","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Irish Government was represented at the Stormont House talks by the Minister for Foreign Affairs, Charles Flanagan TD and Minister Sean Sherlock TD. The Taoiseach, Enda Kenny, and Tánaiste Joan Burton, attended along with the Prime Minister, on 11-12 December. The Irish Government attended as one of the signatories to the Belfast Agreement. As has been previously set out to the Noble Lord, their participation was in accordance with the three stranded approach to Northern Ireland affairs which the Government has a manifesto pledge to uphold.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-06-30T11:26:43.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384509/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384509/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-22","Stormont House Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 18 June (HL393), what is the full list of those who attended the talks leading up to the Stormont House Agreement on behalf of the government of Ireland; and who invited them.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384510","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-03","<p>The UK was a founder member of the then Committee for Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE - later renamed Organisation - OSCE in 1994) when it was created in 1975, and has been an active participating State throughout its existence.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The OSCE is, and continues to be, an important means of pursuing a range of UK policy priorities, to promote UK values on human rights and democracy, our interests in conventional arms control, along with wider European security issues and conflict prevention.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK plays an influential role in the OSCE. We work to defend OSCE commitments and principles, the OSCE institutions, and challenge failure to respect obligations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The OSCE oversees a number of commitments on how participating States have agreed to behave towards each other and towards their citizens. Though these norms are regularly breached, their existence provides an important standard against which the people of the participating States can attempt to hold their leaders accountable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Ongoing OSCE discussion of opportunities and challenges to the future of European security also contribute to UK policy objectives. The OSCE remains the main multilateral forum that brings together 57 countries in the Euro-Atlantic area, including Russia, the United States and EU member states, on a range of key security issues and is home to a number of interlocking instruments which form the basis for conventional arms control across the Euro-Atlantic area.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-03T13:57:11.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384510/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384510/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-22","Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they participate in the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe; and, if so, whether participating has changed their policies in any way.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384511","Department of Health","false","2015-07-02","<p>Exposure to secondhand smoke is a serious health hazard. More than 50 carcinogens have been identified in secondhand smoke.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The report of the United States Surgeon General titled <em>The health consequences of involuntary exposure to tobacco smoke</em> concluded that secondhand smoke causes premature death and disease in children and adults who do not smoke. The scientific evidence indicates that there is no risk-free level of exposure to secondhand smoke. Children exposed to secondhand smoke are at an increased risk for sudden infant death syndrome, acute respiratory infections, ear problems and more severe asthma. Smoking by parents causes respiratory symptoms and slows lung growth in children. Exposure of adults to secondhand smoke has immediate adverse effects on the cardiovascular system and causes coronary heart disease and lung cancer. Legislation to stop smoking in vehicles carrying children will come into force in England on 1 October 2015.</p><p> </p><p><br> The report of the Royal College of Physicians titled <em>Going smoke-free: The medical case for clean air in the home, at work and in public places</em> included estimates that secondhand smoke exposure caused approximately 12,200 deaths in the United Kingdom in 2003, and that the majority of these deaths occurred as a result of exposure to secondhand smoke in the home. These estimates were made prior to the introduction of smokefree legislation in England in 2007. Over the past decade, the proportion of smokers who say that they do not smoke in the home has increased.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The evidence is clear that smokefree legislation in England has had beneficial effects on health, as set out in the report <em>The Impact of smokefree legislation in England: evidence review</em> which was published alongside the <em>“Tobacco Control Plan for England”</em> in March 2011. The reports referred to have already been placed in the Library.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-02T15:48:46.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384511/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384511/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Passive Smoking: Death","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what their assessment is of the number of people who have died from passive smoking in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384512","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-06","<p>As part of their Retirement Income Market Study, the Financial Conduct Authority have committed to monitoring the retirement market in order to assess consumer behaviour and outcomes; and to use their wide-ranging powers to intervene where necessary. The Treasury will also be consulting in July to ensure that people are treated fairly when moving their pension to a company that offers them flexible options and are not charged excessive early exit penalties.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-07-06T16:38:25.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384512/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384512/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what systems are in place to assess and evaluate the new pension freedoms.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384513","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-06","<p /> <p>The Disability Confident campaign makes the business case for recruiting and retaining more disabled people and aims to increase the number of employers taking positive action to be more disability confident. We are not able to measure the number of disabled people moving into employment as a direct result of it, but the campaign is an important contributor towards our commitment to halve the gap between the employment rates of disabled and non-disabled people.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2015-07-06T12:00:19.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384513/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384513/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-22","Employment: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people they expect to find jobs as a result of the Disability Confident campaign.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384514","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Court rejected two of the three legal grounds brought by the claimants, finding that their human rights had not been breached and not awarding damages.</p><p> </p><p>Where the Court found that the historic delay for the two claimants was unlawful, they also ruled that they are not “test cases” and it would be inappropriate to make wider findings.</p><p> </p><p>The Court accepted that the Government had made significant improvements to the Personal Independence Payment (PIP) process and there are now no inherent failings in the system.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of these improvements, the average time taken for a claimant to be assessed by an assessment provider has fallen by more than three quarters since June 2014. In April 2015, the average new claimant was waiting 5 weeks for their PIP assessment – well within the 16 week target set by the Secretary of State.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2015-06-30T15:50:02.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384514/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384514/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-22","Personal Independence Payment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recent High Court ruling regarding delays in Personal Independence Payments.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384515","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2015-06-29","<p>The tiles in St Stephen’s Hall were not in a special pattern to mark the spot of Spencer Perceval’s assassination as some have suggested; they were poor repairs done after the original tiles were damaged during the Second World War. A plaque has been erected in St Stephen’s Hall near the spot where Spencer Perceval was assassinated.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Sewel",,"2015-06-29T16:33:14.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384515/answer","Biography information for Lord Sewel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384515/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2015-06-22","Spencer Perceval","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees why the mispatterned tile which was a memorial of the spot where Prime Minister Spencer Perceval was assassinated has been removed from St Stephen's Hall; and whether it can be replaced.","false","Biography information for Lord Butler of Brockwell",,"Lord Butler of Brockwell","HL726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384516","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-06","<p /> <p>This calculation was derived from an independent review commissioned by the Department for Education.</p><p> </p><p>The information is available in the Department for Education’s Relationship Support Interventions Evaluation, published in 2014. This sets out a detailed explanation of how the savings were calculated using a cost benefit analysis.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2015-07-06T13:22:18.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384516/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384516/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-22","Families","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Altmann on 22 June, how they have calculated that £1 spent on advice yields approximately £11.50 in savings.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384517","Department of Health","false","2015-07-06","<p><br> We have legislated for parity of esteem between mental and physical health via the Health and Social Care Act 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The 2014-15 Mandate to NHS England sets a clear objective for NHS England to deliver parity of esteem. The Mandate also makes clear that ‘everyone who needs it should have timely access to evidence-based [mental health] services’.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have invested over £120 million in order to introduce for the first time waiting times standards for a number of mental health services – a very significant milestone on the road to parity.</p><p> </p><p><br> The Government will hold the National Health Service to account for achieving the objectives set out in the NHS Mandate for 2014-15 and the refreshed Mandate for 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p><br> Spending on mental health is estimated to have increased by £302 million in 2014-15, with total mental health spending rising from £11.362 billion in 2013-14 to £11.664 billion planned in 2014-15, an increase of 0.6% in real terms. In the planning requirements for 2015-16, commissioners were required to invest additionally in mental health in line with their increase in allocation. The total planned additional spend is £376 million, an increase of 4.5%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England published planning guidance for 2015-16 which made the expectation clear that each clinical commissioning group’s (CCGs) spending on mental health services in 2015-16 should increase in real terms, and grow by at least the same percentage as each CCG’s allocation increase.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to increasing the primary and community care workforce to make available 10,000 primary care staff including an estimated 5,000 more doctors working in general practice by 2020. We have backed this commitment with £10 million of funding and a joint plan between NHS England, Health Education England, the Royal College of General Practitioners and the British Medical Association, to increase the GP workforce.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) is the annual reward and incentive programme detailing GP practice achievement results. A number of mental health indicators are included in the QOF. It rewards practices for the provision of quality care and helps to standardise improvements in the delivery of clinical care. The mental health indicators help to drive improvements in the care and monitoring of patients with depression, bipolar disorder, psychoses and other mental illnesses.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-06T13:20:48.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384517/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384517/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to achieve "parity of esteem" between acute and mental health services, both with regard to access and the provision of health services, through the increase in the number of general practitioners in primary care settings.","false","Biography information for Baroness Manzoor",,"Baroness Manzoor","HL728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384518","Attorney General","false","2015-06-29","<p>It would not be in the public interest to disclose any specific retail or real estate valuation information, as this information is commercially sensitive and any disclosure could adversely affect the Government’s future ability to negotiate efficiencies and achieve value for money to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service has a total owned and leased estate of 81,085 sq metres. Of that estate 9.3% is currently not in regular use. The total rental cost of those sites not in regular use is £961,235 (ex VAT).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The proportion of the office space owned or leased by The Government Legal Department (GLD) which is not in regular use comprises 9% of the total estate. The rental value of all unused office space is £248,680.69.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Both departments keep their estates under regular review and expect to have significantly reduced the proportion of office space which is not in regular use by December 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The remaining Law Officers’ Departments do not own or lease any property which is not in regular use.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2015-06-29T13:05:43.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384518/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384518/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-06-22","Attorney General: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by the Law Officers' Departments is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of the Law Officers' Departments most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384519","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-30","<p>The core Department of Business Innovation and Skills (BIS Core) does not own any freehold office space.</p><p>Core BIS has 212.34 square metres of vacant office space in Fleetbank House. This space is currently under negotiation to sub-let which will mean all BIS office space is in regular use. This vacant space represents 0.002% of core BIS total office space.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-30T15:36:23.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384519/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384519/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Department of Business, Innovation and Skills: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384520","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Since 2010 the Government has been selling unnecessary properties. We have got out of hundreds of properties which were previously under-occupied or superfluous to needs. We now publish more details than ever before on how Departments are using their buildings. Our work to rationalise the Government's property estate has resulted in the exit of 2,018 buildings since 2010, raising £1.4 billion in capital receipts and generating £625 million in running costs savings up to 31 March 2014.</p><p>The Government residual estate is part of the Cabinet Office. Birch House in Bristol is office space that is currently vacant. The Government Property Unit (part of the Cabinet Office) is working to dispose of this and other unnecessary properties. We are also considering the long term strategy for 36 Whitehall and ensuring the optimum use of this building within the core Whitehall estate. The remainder of the Cabinet Office estate is defined as Core Estate and as such is fully utilised to deliver departmental functions.</p><p>Information about property valuations for the Cabinet Office's Land and Buildings, which have been audited by the National Audit Office, are contained in the Cabinet Office annual report and accounts 2013-14, available from the Libraries in the House and online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2013-to-2014</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","3480","2015-06-30T16:01:32.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384520/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384520/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-22","Cabinet Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384521","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-30","<p>Holdings of real estate are assessed as either being required to deliver departmental functions (forming the Core estate) or surplus to this requirement (Non-Core). There is no system for classifying frequency of use. The government's top priority for surplus holdings is to reduce property costs by exiting leasehold agreements, selling freeholds or by sub-letting to external tenants. We have a portal - Find Me Some Government Space (https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property) – for more efficient marketing of surplus land and buildings. This is searchable by developers, community groups and the general public.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is considered not to be in the public interest to disclose real estate valuation reports, as this information can be commercially sensitive and any disclosure could adversely affect the Government’s future ability to negotiate efficiencies and achieve value for money to the taxpayer. However, the value of HM Treasury’s land and buildings is available in its annual report and accounts, which is accessible on www.gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-30T14:07:23.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384521/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384521/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Treasury: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384522","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-10","<p>The Department does not have unused freehold or leasehold office space and it does not hold a market value assessment for the properties held.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010 the Department has had considerable success in reducing the cost of its estate. We have saved:</p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>£16 million per year by surrendering seven leasehold offices;</li><li>£24 million per year for Government by moving the Department to Marsham Street;</li><li>£10.9 million per year by subletting surplus leasehold office space.</li></ul>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2015-07-10T13:22:27.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384522/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384522/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Department for Communities and Local Government: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384523","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>All of the space in the Department's offices is in regular use.</p><p> </p><p>It would not be in the public interest to disclose any specific retail or real estate valuation information, as this information is commercially sensitive and any disclosure could adversely affect the Government’s future ability to negotiate efficiencies and achieve value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T14:39:48.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384523/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384523/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-22","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384524","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-29","<p>This information is being withheld for the purpose of safeguarding national security.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-29T15:25:57.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384524/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384524/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-22","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, to what ongoing tasks in which countries the Ministry of Defence Police Special Escort Group have been assigned.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384525","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-29","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by the then Minister for International Security Strategy (Dr Andrew Murrison) on 12 February 2014 (Official Report, column 698W).</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-29T15:25:21.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384525/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384525/answer","HOC 3470 Hansard Extract 12 February 2014.doc","Buildings","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384525/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-22","Ministry of Defence: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384526","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>Since May 2010 the department has reduced the size of its estate from 30 properties, at a cost of circa £51m per annum, to six properties costing circa £31m per annum. This has been achieved by reducing the amount of space the department uses, by surrendering unwanted premises to landlords and through sub-letting vacant space to other organisations. The department plans to dispose of a further three vacated premises. These are:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Building</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Tenure</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Comment</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Castle View House, Runcorn</p><p> </p><p>9,953 Sq M (12% of DfE Estate)</p></td><td><p>Freehold</p></td><td><p>The site has been marketed to the public and private sectors and is currently under offer.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mowden Hall, Darlington</p><p> </p><p>6,389 Sq M (7.5% of DfE Estate)</p></td><td><p>Freehold</p></td><td><p>Part of the site already houses a Free School. When fully vacated, the remainder of the site will be handed to the Homes and Communities Agency in September 2015 for new homes.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Trust Court, Histon</p><p> </p><p>429 Sq M (0.5% of DfE Estate)</p></td><td><p>Leasehold</p></td><td><p>The site will be surrendered to the landlord at lease expiry in 2016.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The vacated properties represent 20% of the department’s estate, with an annual rental value of £138,968. This will reduce to 0.5% when the anticipated freehold disposals are concluded this calendar year.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold market rental values for properties it leases. For commercial reasons we are unable to release the value of the freehold properties.</p><p> </p><p>The department also plans to vacate Sanctuary Buildings at lease expiry in 2017 and relocate to a government owned freehold building, which will generate a further saving of circa £8.5m per year for the department and £19m for government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-25T13:25:50.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384526/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384526/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-22","Department for Education: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by her Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384527","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Department of Energy &amp; Climate Change (DECC) has no office space which is not in regular use.</p><p>All of DECC’s property is leased aside from 55 Whitehall. This is a Crown Estate building. The Department cannot release real estate valuation as this is considered to be commercially sensitive.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-07T12:58:22.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384527/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384527/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by her Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384528","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-30","<p>Defra offices are assessed as either being required to deliver departmental functions (forming the core estate) or surplus to this requirement (non-core).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra's priority for surplus holdings is to reduce property costs by exiting leasehold agreements, selling freeholds or by sub-letting to external tenants. The proportion of Defra office property vacant, held by the Defra property holding centre, as at 29<sup>th</sup> June is 5.76%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The actual rental depends on how long the office space would be vacant, making it difficult to calculate, with no rental values held for the freehold office estate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government Property Unit (GPU) has created a portal - Find Me Some Government Space (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property</a>) - for more efficient marketing of surplus land and buildings. This is searchable by developers, community groups and the general public.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-30T16:09:58.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384528/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384528/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-22","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by her Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384529","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>The majority of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO)'s UK office space is always in regular use. Work is currently underway to consolidate our London headquarters into one building in King Charles Street by the beginning of November this year. This will save around £5 million a year in running costs for the FCO and free up the Old Admiralty Building for use by another Government Department. Staff are being moved between King Charles Street and the Old Admiralty Building while refurbishments take place and there is no spare office space in either of these buildings. Once the project is completed, the King Charles Street offices are expected to be fully occupied.</p><p>Overseas, the FCO runs an estate comprising about 4,800 properties in over 260 locations worldwide. Our portfolio is regularly reviewed to ensure we are getting value for money and maintaining a fit-for-purpose estate.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-30T14:56:58.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384529/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384529/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-22","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384530","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>The proportion of office space owned or leased by the Department and not in regular use is 0.66%. Rental information is commercially sensitive and would adversely affect Her Majesty’s Governments future ability to negotiate efficiencies and achieve value for money to the taxpayer. As this is a leasehold property, we do not have the retail value of the office space.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has not undertaken a recent valuation of its real estate.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>On 31 March 2014, only 2.4% (204,327 sq m) of space was vacant across the mandated Civil Estate, compared with the national private and public sector average of 8.8%</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to review its estate in order to reduce costs. The Department has adopted a policy of co-locating with other organisations and most of the buildings it is responsible for contain a number of our arm’s length bodies. It also looks to reduce property costs by exiting leasehold agreements, or by sub-letting to external tenants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has contributed to the Government’s Strategic Land and Property Review. Departments have already committed to reforms expected to release land worth £3.5 billion between 2015 and 2020, with a further £1.5 billion expected to be identified following the outcome of operational reviews. This was updated at Autumn Statement, with a new ambition of £5 - 6 billion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government Property Unit has created a portal - Find Me Some Government Space (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property</a>) - for more efficient marketing of surplus land and buildings. This is searchable by developers, community groups and the general public.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further information on the efficiency and sustainability of property in the government's civil estate is published in our State of the Estate Report 2013 - 2014 available here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-30T16:16:25.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384530/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384530/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Department of Health: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384531","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Spending on mental health is estimated to have increased by £302 million in 2014/15, with total mental health spending rising from £11.362 billion in 2013/14 to £11.664 billion planned in 2014/15, an increase of 0.6% in real terms. In the planning requirements for 2015/16, commissioners were required to invest additionally in mental health in line with their increase in allocation. The total planned additional spend is £376 million, an increase of 4.5%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) programme aims to help adults with common mental health conditions, including anxiety and depression, to recover using a range of psychological therapies or “talking therapies” recommended by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) in their clinical guidelines. These include Cognitive Behavioural Therapy, Interpersonal Therapy, Brief Dynamic Interpersonal Therapy, Couple Therapy for depression and counselling for depression. The national roll out of the IAPT programme began in 2008.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the spending review period 2010-2015 the IAPT programme received over £460 million of government investment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The NHS Mandate for 2015/16 and ‘Achieving Better Access to Mental Health Services by 2020’ included the commitment to introduce the first access and waiting times for mental health in 2015/16. This was accompanied by a £120 million investment – an investment of £40 million new money in 2014/15 to lay the groundwork for introducing the standards, and £80 million in 2015/16 that will be released out of existing NHS England budgets. One of the standards is that 75% of people referred to the IAPT programme will be treated within six weeks of referral, and 95% will be treated within 18 weeks of referral.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Achieving better access to mental health services by 2020 </em>published in October 2014, set the expectation that, by 2020, all acute trusts will have in place liaison psychiatry services for all ages appropriate to the size, acuity and specialty of the hospital, including in Emergency Departments. Liaison psychiatry services see mental health staff working alongside acute hospital staff including in Emergency Departments. NHS England is supporting this aim by targeting £30 million investment in 2015/16 to enable a greater number of acute hospitals to establish effective models of liaison psychiatry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) is the annual reward and incentive programme detailing GP practice achievements. A number of mental health indicators are included in the QOF. It rewards practices for the provision of quality care and helps to standardise improvements in the delivery of clinical care. The mental health indicators help to drive improvements in the care and monitoring of patients with depression, bipolar disorder, psychoses and other mental illnesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NICE published the guideline <em>Depression in adults: The treatment and management of depression in adults</em> in October 2009. The guidance recommends that healthcare professionals be alert to possible depression, particularly in people with a past history of depression or a chronic physical health problem with associated functional impairment. It also recommends that they consider asking people who may have depression two pertinent questions about their well-being in the past month. If a person answers ‘yes’ to either of these questions then the practitioner should either review the patient’s mental state and associated functional, interpersonal and social difficulties themselves or refer the patient to a competent mental health assessor to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","3439 ; 3511","2015-06-30T14:12:38.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384531/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384531/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Depressive Illnesses: Diagnosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve the diagnosis of depression at GP surgeries when the patient has not presented with that condition in the first instance.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384532","Home Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>While holdings are not classified against frequency of use, 0.34% by area of the Home Office’s office estate can be assessed as not in regular use with an estimated rental value of £125,000 per annum. It is all leased with no retail element and is surplus for disposal. The office estate has been significantly rationalised since 2010 with the priority given to exiting leasehold buildings or sub-lettings to non-Home Office occupiers. The Department fully supports the Governments’ Strategic Land and Property Review which is expected to release land worth £3.5 billion by 2020.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-06-30T15:57:05.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384532/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384532/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-22","Home Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by her Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384533","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-30","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) is constantly seeking ways of reducing its rental liability. It is currently engaged in an active programme to rationalise its estate including exiting properties on lease expiry or break option if earlier in accordance with Cabinet Office National Property Controls.</p><p> </p><p>Details of MoJ’s vacant properties including the tenure, size and availability, are recorded on the Central Government property database, Epims. These records are available via the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a title="http://www.data.gov.uk/dataset/epims" href="http://www.data.gov.uk/dataset/epims" target="_blank">www.data.gov.uk/dataset/epims</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the retail value of unused office space, including that within surplus court buildings, is not collected centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the valuation of land and property assets is available in the Ministry of Justice Report and Accounts via the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministry-of-justice-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministry-of-justice-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministry-of-justice-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-06-30T14:12:04.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384533/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384533/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-22","Ministry of Justice: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384534","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>Following recent accommodation changes in the Northern Ireland Office (NIO), all office space owned or leased by the Department is in regular use.</p><p>This Government is committed to reducing and rationalising its Estate to improve efficiency and release value. My Department has vacated satellite offices in central Belfast and staff have been relocated within existing premises in the Stormont Estate to ensure that all office space is effectively utilised, whilst ensuring that meeting space is available for ongoing political discussions.</p><p>The Department’s estate is restricted to Hillsborough Castle and its valuation is disclosed in the NIO Annual Report and Accounts. The most recent copy published is for the financial year ended 31 March 2014 which can be obtained at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/332945/NIO_Annual_Report___Accounts_2013-14.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/332945/NIO_Annual_Report___Accounts_2013-14.pdf</a> .</p><p>Further information on the efficiency and sustainability of property in the government’s civil estate is published in the “State of the Estate Report 2013-14” which can be obtained at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-29T15:19:35.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384534/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384534/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-22","Northern Ireland Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by her Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384535","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-29","<p>DFID occupies two buildings in the UK, one in Whitehall, London and the other in East Kilbride. We hold the leasehold on both properties and therefore no rent is paid.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-29T16:21:23.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384535/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384535/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-22","Department for International Development: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by her Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if she will place in the Library a copy of her most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384536","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.</p><p>Since 2010 the Government has been selling unnecessary properties. We have got out of hundreds of properties which were previously under-occupied or superfluous to needs. We now publish more details than ever before on how Departments are using their buildings. Our work to rationalise the Government's property estate has resulted in the exit of 2,018 buildings since 2010, raising £1.4 billion in capital receipts and generating £625 million in running costs savings up to 31 March 2014.</p><p>The Government residual estate is part of the Cabinet Office. Birch House in Bristol is office space that is currently vacant. The Government Property Unit (part of the Cabinet Office) is working to dispose of this and other unnecessary properties. We are also considering the long term strategy for 36 Whitehall and ensuring the optimum use of this building within the core Whitehall estate. The remainder of the Cabinet Office estate is defined as Core Estate and as such is fully utilised to deliver departmental functions.</p><p>Information about property valuations for the Cabinet Office's Land and Buildings, which have been audited by the National Audit Office, are contained in the Cabinet Office annual report and accounts 2013-14, available from the Libraries in the House and online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-annual-report-and-accounts-2013-to-2014</a></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","3467","2015-06-30T16:01:32.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384536/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384536/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-22","Prime Minister: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by 10 Downing Street is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384537","Scotland Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Scotland Office occupies two leasehold buildings, one in Edinburgh and one in London. The Edinburgh building is fully occupied by the Scotland Office and other government bodies which contribute towards its cost. The London building was fully occupied by the Scotland Office, the Office of the Advocate General and other government bodies until recently when the Deputy Prime Minister’s Office ceased to occupy space in the building. The Scotland Office is now in discussion with other government bodies to occupy this space. Under the terms of the lease the space may not be let commercially, but may only be used by Crown bodies. The retail value is a matter for the building’s owners.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-06-25T14:18:29.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384537/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384537/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-22","Scotland Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384538","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>As part of the Government’s Transparency Agenda information about Department for Transport properties is published on the data.gov.uk website. Information on surplus properties owned and leased by the Department is available via the following web link:</p><p><a href="http://data.gov.uk/dataset/epims" target="_blank">http://data.gov.uk/dataset/epims</a></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>Information on the valuation of land and property assets is available in the Department for Transport Annual Report and Accounts:</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-for-transport-annual-report-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-for-transport-annual-report-and-accounts</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-29T13:50:45.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384538/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384538/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Department for Transport: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384539","Wales Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>All space in the Wales Office’s London and Cardiff offices is in regular use. The London office is owned by the Department, and we lease accommodation in Cardiff. The Valuation Office Agency undertook a valuation of the London office (land and buildings) on 31 March 2014, and valued it at £4,125,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2015-06-29T13:58:10.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384539/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384539/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-06-22","Wales Office: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384540","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-29","<p /> <p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not own any buildings. The Department’s estate was sold (freehold, feuhold and long leasehold interests) or transferred (short leasehold interests) to Telereal Trillium under a PFI contract known as “PRIME” in 1998 and further in 2003.</p><p> </p><p>The proportion of leasehold space which is not in regular use is approximately 2 per cent of the total estate of 1,482,959 sqm that the Department occupies. All such space is registered on the Government Property Unit’s database e-PIMS. The usage of the estate is under constant review and its use changes with the needs of the business.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's top priority for surplus space is to reduce property costs by exiting leasehold agreements, selling freeholds or by sub-letting to external tenants.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Government’s Strategic Land and Property Review (SLPR), Departments have already committed to reforms expected to release land worth £3.5 billion between 2015 and 2020, with a further £1.5 billion expected to be identified following the outcome of operational reviews. This was updated at Autumn Statement, with a new ambition of releasing land to the value of £5 - 6 billion.</p><p> </p><p>GPU has created a portal - Find Me Some Government Space (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/find-government-property</a>) - for more efficient marketing of surplus land and buildings. This is searchable by developers, community groups and the general public.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on the efficiency and sustainability of property in the Government's civil estate is published in our State of the Estate Report 2013 - 2014 available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/state-of-the-estate-2014</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>I am advised that it is not in the public interest to disclose rental, retail or real estate valuation information, so will not be placing a copy of this information in the Library. This information is commercially sensitive and any disclosure would adversely affect the Government’s future ability to negotiate efficiencies and achieve value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-29T15:54:38.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384540/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384540/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-22","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of the office space owned or leased by his Department is not in regular use; what the total (a) rental and (b) retail value is of all such office space; and if he will place in the Library a copy of his most recent departmental real estate valuation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","3485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384541","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-24","<p /> <p>The potential implications of closing the Independent Living Fund are set out clearly in the Equality Analysis published on 6 March 2014.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-06-24T12:55:45.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384541/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384541/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-22","Independent Living Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the closure of the Independent Living Fund on people previously in receipt of that funding who used it to pay for assistance required to live in the community.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","3434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384543","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>There are 131 stations managed by Abellio Greater Anglia, whilst their services call at 147 stations. Of those 131 stations 67 have staffed ticket offices.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T09:52:21.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384543/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384543/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many stations on the Greater Anglia rail franchise have ticket offices.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384544","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The current Direct Award for the Greater Anglia franchise which started in July 2014 is a premium paying franchise, therefore there is no cost to the Government.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T09:56:43.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384544/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384544/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost to the Government of the new Greater Anglia rail franchise.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384545","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Following the ticket vending machine summit held in December with the rail industry, the industry has committed to improving and simplifying the rail ticketing system so that passengers can be confident of making the right choice when they buy their tickets from any retail outlet. As part of this, rail operators have agreed to improve the information passengers receive when buying tickets from ticket machines. The Office of Rail and Road (ORR) has also issued a Code of Practice on ticket retail information, which the industry is expected to follow. We are closely monitoring the progress the industry is making.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T13:32:01.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384545/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384545/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that ticket machines on the Greater Anglia rail franchise provide the same value and ticketing options as ticket offices.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384546","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Our current estimate of the cost for the tendering process is £6.63m through to June 2016. This is in line with the costs of other franchising projects, taking into account recommendations made in Richard Brown’s Review into Rail Franchising. The actual spend will be published annually in our Departmental accounts. With regard to bidders costs, the Department makes no such estimate - this is an internal matter for bidders,</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-29T09:49:00.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384546/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384546/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost to the (a) Government and (b) bidders of the tendering process for the new Greater Anglia rail franchise.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384547","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>The Department is open to receiving bids for the East Anglia franchise containing commitments to pay the living wage but salary and benefit arrangements are a matter for employers to determine.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-25T13:26:10.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384547/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384547/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will ensure that bidders for the next contract for the Greater Anglia rail passenger service take steps so that the living wage is paid through the contract chain.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384548","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>There are 131 stations managed by Abellio Greater Anglia, whilst their services call at 147 stations. Of those 131 stations, under the terms of the Franchise Agreement, 67 have staffed ticket offices. All other staffing decisions are a matter for the operator and they have no need to inform us of their decisions.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2015-06-25T13:33:30.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384548/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384548/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Railways: East of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many stations there are on the Greater Anglia rail franchise; and how many of those stations are unstaffed.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384549","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>As of 12 June 2015, there are 3,133 staff employed by Abellio Greater Anglia (AGA). On the AGA Franchise, the Department monitors the staffing levels of guards and train crew (1090 on 12 June), cleaning staff (220 on 12 June) and catering staff (57 on 12 June). The Department does not monitor the other categories to this level of granularity.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","3408","2015-06-25T13:16:11.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384549/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384549/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Abellio Greater Anglia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff are employed by Greater Anglia rail passenger services.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384550","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-25","<p>As of 12 June 2015, there are 3,133 staff employed by Abellio Greater Anglia (AGA). On the AGA Franchise, the Department monitors the staffing levels of guards and train crew (1090 on 12 June), cleaning staff (220 on 12 June) and catering staff (57 on 12 June). The Department does not monitor the other categories to this level of granularity.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","3411","2015-06-25T13:16:11.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384550/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384550/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Abellio Greater Anglia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff are employed by Greater Anglia rail passenger services as (a) station staff, (b) ticket office staff, (c) guards or train crew, (d) cleaning staff, (e) catering staff, (f) security staff, (g) administrative staff and (h) managerial staff.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","3408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384551","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The table below shows the vehicle excise duty and the total fine income collected by the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA)</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Vehicle Excise Duty Collected</p></td><td><p>Fines</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£5,782 million</p></td><td><p>£49 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£5,932 million</p></td><td><p>£38 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£6,013 million</p></td><td><p>£42 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£6,052 million</p></td><td><p>£41 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£6,123 million</p></td><td><p>£35 Million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T09:31:17.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384551/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384551/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2015 to Question 2298, how much DVLA received from vehicle excise duty (a) fees and (b) fines in each of the most recent five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384552","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>The table below shows the amount of vehicle excise duty collected by the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) over the last five years. All the duty collected is paid in full to HM Treasury.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Vehicle Excise Duty Collected</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£5,782 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£5,932 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£6,013 million,</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£6,052 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£6,123 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-06-29T09:37:24.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384552/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384552/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 19 June 2015 to Question 2298, what income the DVLA received from vehicle excise duty; and what that income has been used for in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384553","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The Collaborative Tuberculosis Strategy for England 2015-2020 has identified the need for provision of specific and targeted national outreach interventions to help tackle tuberculosis (TB) in under-served populations. Proposals to create this national plan will be developed in conjunction with relevant stakeholders. The specific details of these national service developments are in progress and the location of any regional TB outreach service is not yet confirmed.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-30T14:17:07.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384553/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384553/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Tuberculosis: Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will establish a regional TB outreach service based in the Midlands.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384554","Department of Health","false","2015-06-25","<p>Patients are referred to these centres each year through one of the most developed commissioning programmes for proton beam therapy (PBT) abroad in the world. NHS England monitors these services carefully and is confident that they offer a high quality holistic service. This is particularly important because the treatment takes about 10 weeks.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England is not able to provide information broken down by the number of patients per site, per year, as this is not held in the format requested. Additionally, due to the small number of patients involved (in particular for the centre in Switzerland), there would be a risk of providing patient identifiable information.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Patients sent abroad for PBT over the last five years is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>74</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>99</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>124</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>139</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The costs of treatment and accommodation are incurred as part of the package of treatment, and are currently approximately £75,000 per patient.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In April 2012, the Secretary of State announced that £250 million will be invested to build PBT facilities at The Christie Hospital in Manchester and University College London Hospitals. Work has already started and the first facility is due to become operational in 2018.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-25T16:03:29.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384554/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384554/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many referrals the NHS made to each of the two American and one Swiss centres from which it commissions proton beam therapy in each of the last five years for which figures are available; what the cost of purchasing that treatment from each such centre in each such year was; and what the cost to the NHS was of (a) travel, (b) accommodation and (c) other expenses relating to treatment provided at each such centre in each such year.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384555","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency has made no estimate of the number of game farms using un-enriched cages for partridges. However, four game farms have been inspected as a result of welfare concerns since June 2014. So far only one has resulted in action being taken with a follow-up visit to be undertaken in July 2015. Before June 2014, game farms were not recorded separately from certain other farmed species, so it is not possible to separate out such establishments.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","3428","2015-06-30T10:06:00.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384555/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384555/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-22","Game: Farms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many game farms were assessed by the Animal and Plant Health Agency as using un-enriched raised laying cages for partridge breeding pairs in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384556","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-30","<p>No estimate has been made of the number of game farms using un-enriched cages for breeding partridges in breach of the <em>Code of Practice for the Welfare of Gamebirds Reared for Sporting Purposes</em>.</p><p> </p><p>However, four game farms have been inspected as a result of welfare concerns since June 2014. The Defra funded research into cage-based breeding for game birds will be published in due course and will be used to help inform the review of the gamebirds code of practice.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","3518","2015-06-30T10:18:50.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384556/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384556/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-22","Game: Farms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of game farms in England and Wales using un-enriched raised laying cages for partridge breeding pairs; and what steps she is taking to prevent such practices.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384557","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency has made no estimate of the number of game farms using un-enriched cages for partridges. However, four game farms have been inspected as a result of welfare concerns since June 2014. So far only one has resulted in action being taken with a follow-up visit to be undertaken in July 2015. Before June 2014, game farms were not recorded separately from certain other farmed species, so it is not possible to separate out such establishments.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","3426","2015-06-30T10:06:00.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384557/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384557/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-22","Game: Farms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many visits to English and Welsh pheasant and partridge game farms the Animal and Plant Health Agency made in each of the last five years for which figures are available; how many breaches of the Animal Welfare Act 2006 and its Code of Practice for Gamebirds Reared for Sporting Purposes were discovered during those visits; what those breaches were; and what action was taken to address each such breach.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384558","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Work is currently underway with relevant stakeholders as part of the Collaborative Tuberculosis Strategy for England’s implementation process, to develop proposals for creating a national tuberculosis outreach service as soon as possible.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-30T14:06:21.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384558/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384558/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Tuberculosis: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for the establishment of a national TB outreach service.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384559","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>The mobile x-ray unit for diagnosing tuberculosis in underserved populations is visiting Birmingham week commencing 20 July 2015 for five days. During this period the unit will screen underserved populations in Birmingham, Sandwell and Dudley.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-30T13:14:32.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384559/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384559/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Tuberculosis: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the mobile x-ray unit for diagnosing tuberculosis in under-served populations will next visit Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","3423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384560","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-25","<p>I am unable to comment on meetings held with Ministers under the previous Administration. It is an established convention that Minsters of one Administration cannot see the documents of a previous Administration.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Brief details of ministerial meetings with external organisations are all publically available on the Gov.UK website.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-06-25T13:48:06.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384560/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384560/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-22","Bradwell Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what meetings (a) he, (b) his predecessor, (c) Ministers in his Department and (d) officials in his Department have had on the future of the Magnox site at Bradwell in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","3404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384561","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm</a>.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-25T14:37:23.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384561/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384561/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Bradwell Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings (a) he, (b) Ministers in his Department and (c) officials in his Department have had on the future of the Magnox site at Bradwell in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","3405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384562","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-07-07T14:57:07.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384562/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384562/answer","PQ3464 Stevenson.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Living/Working Elsewhere","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384562/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-06-22","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people live in England and work in (a) Scotland and (b) Wales.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384563","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Following the publication in February 2013 of Robert Francis’s report into care at Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Trust, Sir Bruce Keogh led a review of 14 trusts that had high mortality rates. The Keogh Review identified significant problems relating to quality and safety and/or leadership in all of these trusts and in July 2013, the decision was taken to place 11 trusts into ‘special measures’. Special measures is a robust and targeted regime agreed between the Care Quality Commission, Monitor and the NHS Trust Development Authority.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A total of 14 trusts were placed in special measures in 2013. In 2014 an additional four trusts entered special measures and six trusts exited the regime.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To date a total of 21 trusts have been placed in special measures and seven have exited the regime, having shown notable improvements. We believe that special measures is an effective way of confronting poor care and improving performance, often in hospitals that had shown significant issues including before 2010.&quot;</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-30T13:04:49.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384563/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384563/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Hospitals: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospital trusts were in special measures in (a) 2012, (b) 2013 and (c) 2014.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384564","Department for Education","false","2015-06-25","<p>The information requested is not held by the Department for Education. The devolved Scottish and Welsh administrations may hold the information that is requested.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-06-25T13:20:34.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384564/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384564/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-22","Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children who live in England go to school in (a) Scotland and (b) Wales.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384565","Department for Education","false","2015-06-30","<p>The number of academies in England and Cumbria is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Number of open academies<sup>1</sup> by phase in England<sup>2</sup>, January 2013 and January 2014</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="2"><p><em>Primary</em></p><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p><em>Secondary</em></p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p><em>January 2013</em></p></td><td><p><em>January 2014</em></p></td><td><p><em>January 2013</em></p></td><td><p><em>January 2014</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(i) Cumbria local authority</p><p> </p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(ii) England</p><p> </p></td><td><p>1,006</p></td><td><p>1,789</p></td><td><p>1,638</p></td><td><p>1,893</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>Including free schools, university technical colleges and studio schools.</p></li><li><p>The figures provided are for England only. The academies policy does not apply to Wales and education policy in Wales is devolved to the National Assembly for Wales.</p></li></ol><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-06-30T13:42:39.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384565/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384565/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-22","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) primary and (b) secondary school academies there were in (i) Cumbria and (ii) England and Wales in (A) 2012-13 and (B) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384566","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-07","<p>In Cumbria there were 119 onshore wind turbines at the end of March 2013 and 128 turbines at the end of March 2014.</p><p>In the UK there were 3959 onshore wind turbines at the end of March 2013 and 4374 turbines at the end of March 2014.</p><p><em>Source: Renewable Energy Planning Database (REPD), May 2015 extract:</em></p><p><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/renewable-energy-planning-database-monthly-extract" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/renewable-energy-planning-database-monthly-extract</a> </em></p><p>Please note that the REPD captures projects entering planning that are 1MW or larger. Therefore, there may be additional onshore wind turbines not captured by the figures given above where these are smaller than 1MW.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-07T12:41:43.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384566/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384566/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wind Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many onshore wind turbines there were in (a) Cumbria and (b) the UK in (i) 2012-13 and (ii) 2013-14","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384567","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-30T14:19:03.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384567/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384567/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Out of Area Treatment: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people resident in Scotland are registered with a GP in England.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384568","Scotland Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Scotland Office does not hold this information; however it can be obtained from the Higher Education Statistics Authority at <a href="http://www.hesa.ac.uk/" target="_blank">www.hesa.ac.uk</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-06-30T11:49:52.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384568/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384568/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-22","Universities: Student Numbers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many people go to university in Scotland who are resident in (a) Scotland, (b) England and (c) any other EU country.","false","Biography information for John Stevenson","Carlisle","John Stevenson","3390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384569","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-26","<p>Flood Re is on schedule to be established and begin its operational testing phase by July 2015. It will be a matter for the Flood Re team itself, rather than the Secretary of State, to determine when the scheme is ready to accept policies and it will require authorisation by the Prudential Regulation Authority and the Financial Conduct Authority. We understand that the Flood Re team expect this to be in April 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Insurers have agreed to continue to abide by the Statement of Principles which ensures continued access to flood insurance until Flood Re is fully operational.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-06-26T10:22:22.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384569/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384569/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-22","Floods: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she expects to implement the flood reinsurance scheme.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384570","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Corporate Covenant provides an excellent opportunity for businesses and other organisations to declare their support for members of the Armed Forces community. To date, across the UK, more than 590 companies have pledged their support and the number is growing steadily. The Secretary of State for Defence has written to the FTSE 350 companies to challenge them to sign the Corporate Covenent.</p><p>European Union (EU) procurement law does not permit the contract award procedure or any contract condition to discriminate against any supplier in the EU. An obligation to sign up and fulfil the Corporate Covenant is likely to disadvantage suppliers outside the UK, although we encourage potential suppliers to sign up to the pledge in every invitation to tender we issue. This is a voluntary approach that allows each organisation to reach their own decisions about the level of support they provide.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-29T15:35:11.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384570/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384570/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-22","Armed Forces Covenant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy that all government procurement contracts for goods and services include an obligation to sign up to and fulfil the armed forces corporation covenant.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384571","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Government remains committed to seeing an improvement in the provision of access services for video-on-demand (VoD) services. We have been monitoring progress of the provision of access services for VoD content since 2013 through engagement with the Authority for Television On Demand (ATVOD), platform operators and content providers. If ATVOD's 2015 annual survey of VOD Services indicates that significant progress has not been made, then as stated in the Connectivity, Content and Consumers Paper (July 2013) we will consider legislation in 2016.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-30T15:26:46.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384571/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384571/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-22","Digital Broadcasting: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress his Department has made on ensuring digital broadcast media are accessible for people with hearing impairments.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384572","Prime Minister","false","2015-06-25","<p>The conduct of the &quot;Maxwellisation&quot; process is a matter for the independent Chilcot Inquiry.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-06-25T15:25:46.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384572/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384572/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-06-22","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, if he will request from the Chairman of the Chilcot Inquiry a list of the witnesses from whom the inquiry is still waiting for comments on the draft material sent to them; and if he will also request the date in each case when material for approval was last sent.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","3448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384573","Department of Health","false","2015-06-25","<p>An Outline Business Case for the ‘Teaching, Trauma and Tertiary care’ (‘3Ts’) redevelopment at the Royal Sussex County Hospital was approved in May 2014. The Trust has subsequently prepared a Full Business Case (FBC) which needs to be approved before new building works can commence. The FBC requires approval from the NHS Trust Development Authority, the Department and HM Treasury.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-25T14:09:06.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384573/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384573/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Royal Sussex County Hospital: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what approvals are outstanding for new building works at the Royal Sussex County Hospital in Brighton.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","3412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384574","Department of Health","false","2015-06-29","<p>On 2 June 2015, my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health announced a series of measures to tackle the increase in agency spend. These measures include:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- agency staff to be procured only from approved Framework Agreements. Use of off-framework arrangements only permitted in exceptional circumstances;</p><p> </p><p>- those organisations in receipt of financial support or in breach of the licence will have a ceiling placed on the level of spend they are able to incur on agency staff; and</p><p> </p><p>- a rate cap will be set for agency staff, with the cap permitted to be breached only in exceptional circumstances.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The controls on agency spend will begin to be rolled-out from 1 July 2015 and will be fully in place by the start of September. The controls will initially apply to nursing staff but will also apply to other clinical and management staff in due course.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-29T15:29:04.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384574/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384574/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Locums: Employment Agencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to reduce the amount spent on agency locums.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","3429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384575","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Department does not hold any information on the effect of the Immigration Health Surcharge on specific sectors of the United Kingdom workforce, including the National Health Service.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-30T13:01:04.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384575/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384575/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","NHS: Surcharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the Immigration Health Surcharge on employment in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","3430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384576","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>The NHS e-Referral Service replaced the previous electronic system, Choose and Book, on 15 June 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The NHS England Operations Department, with the support of the Health and Social Care Information Centre will take the lead in promoting this service in the future, supporting local health communities to increase their use of the service and providing training, advice and reports to help them become fully electronic.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-30T13:09:35.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384576/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384576/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Patient Choice Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to promote the use of the Choose and Book system.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","3431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384577","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Locum agencies on the Crown Commercial Services Framework Agreement are identified as designated bodies under The Medical Profession (Responsible Officers) (Amendment) Regulations 2013. To comply with these regulations, framework agencies must appoint a responsible officer and fulfil the obligations and provisions of the legislation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A statutory duty of a Responsible Officer is to submit a recommendation to the General Medical Council (GMC) about the fitness to practise of all doctors in the organisation, taking into account guidance set by the GMC. A requirement for being included on the Framework Agreement is that the revalidation of all full-time locum doctors will be carried out by the framework supplier.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-30T14:30:52.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384577/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384577/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Locums: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that the revalidation of all full-time locum doctors is carried out by framework suppliers.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","3432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384578","Home Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>In setting the amount of the charge, the last Government considered the range of health services available without charge to migrants, the valuable contribution migrants make to our country and the need to ensure that the UK remains an attractive destination for global talent.</p><p>Taking these factors into account, the Government set the charge at £200 per annum, per migrant (with a discounted rate of £150 per annum for students). This is well below the average per capita cost to the NHS of treating temporary migrants. It is also below the rate that migrants might expect to pay for health insurance in our competitor countries. An Impact Assessment published in October 2013 (entitled ‘Regulating migrant access to health services in the UK’), provides further detail.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-30T15:52:07.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384578/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384578/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-22","NHS: Surcharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what calculation was made to set the figure of £200 for the Immigration Health Surcharge.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","3433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384579","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-25","<p>The First Secretary of State and Chancellor of the Exchequer attended the 2015 Bilderberg conference in a private capacity.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-25T14:39:21.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384579/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384579/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Bilderberg Group","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the briefing packs received by John Kerr, Rona Fairhead, Ed Balls and himself at this year's Bilderberg Conference.","false","Biography information for Mr Michael Meacher","Oldham West and Royton","Mr Michael Meacher","3370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384580","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Development Consent Order for the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon project includes a number of requirements for the developer to undertake ecological and environmental work before the development authorised by the Order can commence. This is required, among other things, in relation to fish and shellfish, avian enhancement and marine mammals.</p><p>The work is in addition to that undertaken by the developer as part of its application for development consent. The environmental information provided by the applicant can be found on the Planning Inspectorate`s web-site:</p><p><a href="http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/projects/wales/tidal-lagoon-swansea-bay/" target="_blank">http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/projects/wales/tidal-lagoon-swansea-bay/</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T16:26:37.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384580/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384580/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what ecological and environmental studies have been planned on the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon Project.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384581","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-29","<p>The 2012’s Crown Estate UK Wave and Tidal Key Resource Areas study [1] assessed the UK’s theoretical resource for wave energy at 69TWh/year (27 GW).</p><p>The Technology Innovation Needs Assessment (TINA) [2] published in 2012 estimated that wave energy could practically deliver 40-50 TWh/year by 2050. The department is currently working on reviewing the TINAs and a refreshed wave energy TINA is likely to be published later this year.</p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> <a href="http://www.thecrownestate.co.uk/media/5476/uk-wave-and-tidal-key-resource-areas-project.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.thecrownestate.co.uk/media/5476/uk-wave-and-tidal-key-resource-areas-project.pdf</a></em></p><p><strong><em> [</em></strong><strong><em>2]</em></strong> <em><a href="http://www.lowcarboninnovation.co.uk/working_together/technology_focus_areas/marine/" target="_blank">http://www.lowcarboninnovation.co.uk/working_together/technology_focus_areas/marine/</a>.</em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-06-29T16:29:04.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384581/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384581/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-22","Wave Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent research her Department has conducted on energy produced from wave power.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","3361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384582","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence has had no discussions with AGD Systems about a charter arrangement for ex-RAF TriStar aircraft.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2015-06-29T15:34:33.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384582/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384582/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-22","AGD Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions his Department has had with ADG Systems on employing that company's ex-RAF L1011 Tristar aircraft for military contract duties on behalf of the UK Government.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","3417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384583","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>The Stormont House Agreement is clear that the UK Government will make full disclosure to the Historical Investigations Unit. As set out in the Queen’s Speech, the Government is committed to bringing forward legislation in this session to implement the new bodies to deal with the legacy of the past in Northern Ireland. The Historical Investigations Unit will be established after the legislation is enacted, and work is ongoing to ensure that, once established, the Unit receives relevant files as promptly as possible.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-30T10:32:42.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384583/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384583/answer","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384583/answer/previousversion/9340","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-22","Northern Ireland Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when the historical files on the conflict in Northern Ireland will be handed over to the Historical Inquiries Unit; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384584","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-25","<p>I last met the Police Ombudsman in September 2014. Over the course of the meeting we discussed a range of issues of mutual interest including the importance of maintaining dialogue between the Department and the Ombudsman Office on national security matters.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-25T12:21:13.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384584/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384584/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-06-22","Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when she last met the Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland; and what subjects were discussed at that meeting.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","3407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384585","Department for International Development","false","2015-06-29","<p>The UK supports low carbon development though the International Climate Fund to help the poorest countries boost their economies and tackle poverty. Overall, the ICF makes up 7% of the UK aid budget.</p><p> </p><p>Of the total ICF budget 55% has been allocated to climate mitigation programmes, which are predominately related to clean energy, as well as energy efficiency and related activities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID will coordinate and scale up efforts to deliver energy to the 1.2 billion people worldwide with no access to electricity, with a particular focus on the more than 660 million people in Africa without access.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps",,"2015-06-29T16:56:29.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384585/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384585/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-06-22","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of her Department's overseas aid budget is allocated to green energy projects in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384586","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-30","<p>Most planning approvals in Green Belt are non-residential, many in support of agriculture. National planning policy makes clear that most forms of development in Green Belt are inappropriate. Local planning authorities, in consultation with local communities, are in charge of protecting their Green Belt in line with policy in the National Planning Policy Framework. If inappropriate development is proposed, the local planning authority has to determine whether the harm to the Green Belt, and any other harm, would be clearly outweighed by other considerations, and whether there are very special circumstances to justify planning permission.<br><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-30T11:18:47.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384586/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384586/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-22","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the report entitled Green Belt Under Development by Glenigan Constructing Insight, dated August 2014, what assessment he has made of the causes of the changes in the number of planning approvals on the green belt over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","3395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384587","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Public Health England’s (PHE) priority is to continue to raise public awareness of the signs and symptoms of cancer through the Be Clear on Cancer campaigns and to encourage people with those symptoms to see their general practitioner promptly. PHE is looking to understand and address inequalities in screening participation. A national workshop will be set up in the autumn to explore and share current knowledge and devise an action plan. The United Kingdom National Screening Committee has also commissioned an evidence review on inequalities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Advisory Committee on Cervical Cancer will be reviewing the results from the Strategies to increase cervical screening uptake at first invitation (STRATEGIC) trial, an on-going trial to identify and implement key innovations to help encourage uptake in young women who are entering the NHS Cervical Screening Programme at the age of 25. Further work will investigate the offer of self-sampling to non-attendees of all ages in the NHS Cervical Screening Programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","3374","2015-06-30T16:15:11.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384587/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384587/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Health: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Public Health England Marketing Strategy 2014 to 2017, published in July 2014, what discussions he has had with Public Health England about the progress of its work to trial mechanisms for improving screening uptake; and whether improving cervical screening uptake will form part of that trial.","false","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","3373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384588","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>Public Health England’s (PHE) priority is to continue to raise public awareness of the signs and symptoms of cancer through the Be Clear on Cancer campaigns and to encourage people with those symptoms to see their general practitioner promptly. PHE is looking to understand and address inequalities in screening participation. A national workshop will be set up in the autumn to explore and share current knowledge and devise an action plan. The United Kingdom National Screening Committee has also commissioned an evidence review on inequalities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Advisory Committee on Cervical Cancer will be reviewing the results from the Strategies to increase cervical screening uptake at first invitation (STRATEGIC) trial, an on-going trial to identify and implement key innovations to help encourage uptake in young women who are entering the NHS Cervical Screening Programme at the age of 25. Further work will investigate the offer of self-sampling to non-attendees of all ages in the NHS Cervical Screening Programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","3373","2015-06-30T16:15:11.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384588/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384588/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Cervical Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Public Health England Marketing Strategy 2014 to 2017, published in July 2014, what discussions he has had with Public Health England about whether its plan to develop marketing campaigns to drive earlier diagnosis will include a focus on raising awareness of cervical screening across the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","3374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384589","Department of Health","false","2015-06-30","<p>We were fully supportive of Cervical Screening Awareness Week from 15 to 21 June 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It is important that women realise that cervical screening can prevent cervical cancer and we encourage women of screening age (25 to 64) to make an informed decision to attend when invited for screening.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Departmental officials regularly meet with Jo’s Cervical Cancer Trust to discuss cervical cancer issues, including Cervical Screening Awareness Week. In addition, I spoke with the Chief Executive of Jo’s Cervical Cancer Trust following Cervical Screening Awareness Week to reflect on how the week had gone and on future challenges.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-30T13:11:16.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384589/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384589/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-22","Cervical Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will support Cervical Screening Awareness Week.","false","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","3375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384590","Scotland Office","false","2015-06-30","<p>I met with the Secretary of State for Transport on 17 June 2015 to discuss High Speed Rail.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-06-30T11:51:13.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384590/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384590/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-06-22","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Transport on the extension of High Speed 2 to Scotland.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","3377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384591","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Scotland will benefit from high speed services from the moment HS2 opens. When Phase Two is complete HS2 trains will deliver Glasgow/Edinburgh to London journey times of 3hrs 38 minutes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Advice prepared by HS2 Ltd in conjunction with the Department for Transport, Transport Scotland and the Scotland Office on broad options for high speed and upgraded railways to the north of England and Scotland is currently being considered by Ministers and will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We look forward to continued close co-operation with the Scottish Government to optimise the benefits that Scotland gets from a High Speed Britain.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-06-29T13:55:14.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384591/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384591/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-22","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to extend High Speed 2 to Glasgow and Edinburgh.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","3378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384592","Home Office","false","2015-06-29","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-06-29T14:37:50.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384592/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384592/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-22","Immigrants: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many non-EU migrants in (a) Glasgow South constituency and (b) Glasgow earn less than £35,000 annually.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","3414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384593","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-30","<p>HM Revenue and Customs published its latest tax gap estimates on 16 October 2014 in 'Measuring Tax Gaps' 2014 edition.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-30T15:44:57.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384593/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384593/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-22","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the amount in corporation tax lost to the Exchequer through evasion in each financial year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart McDonald","3376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384594","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-25","<p>From April 2013 (when the benefit cap was introduced) to February 2015 (the latest available data) 1,876 single parent households with one child dependant have been capped. Of these, 1,158 households (62%) have a child aged under 5 as at February 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on the number of children aged under 5 is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","3367 ; 3368 ; 3458 ; 3459","2015-06-25T16:27:15.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384594/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/384594/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-22","Social Security Benefits: Lone Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of lone parent families with one child that are affected by the benefit cap have a child who is under five.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","3369"
